                <div class="col-lg-6 col-12 get-in-touch waste-energy">
                    <div>
                        <h3>The waste to energy Process</h3>
                        <p class="mb-50">In a modern WTE plant, municipal solid waste is delivered to the site and stored in closed pits preventing the escape any harmful gases. A crane thoroughly mixes and piles up the waste and leachate is collected separately for treatment. The waste after rests for few days, lowers down its moisture content is than passed on to pre-processing system. Waste is finally segregated and the waste meeting the criteria for energy production is termed as RDF (refused derived fuel) which is used as feed to the boiler. The RDF reaches the feed hoppers with the help of cranes, from there it is pushed onto <span class="content-dots">...</span> <span class="content-hide">  the grate by a ram feeder. A fully integrated control system ensures stable and efficient operation and optimises the fire position on the grate. Once combustion is complete, the inert ash that remains falls into the bottom ash extractor, from where it can be taken to a bunker or storage area for metals recovery and further use. The gases released from the waste are mixed with secondary air and recirculated flue gases above the grate. This assures complete combustion and the lowest CO, NOx and VOC emissions. Recirculation of flue gases also increases the plant’s energy efficiency. The energy released is used to produce superheated steam, which is expanded in a turbine generator to generate electricity. Flue gases are then cleaned to the strictest standards and are continuously monitored before being released at the stack.</span> &nbsp;<span class="content-readmore">read more</span></p>
